{"parse":{"title":"Relative index of inequality","pageid":29854878,"revid":817680358,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">\"RII\" redirects here. For the Bengali actress, see <a href=\"/wiki/Rii_Sen\" title=\"Rii Sen\">Rii Sen</a>.</div>\n<p>The <b>relative index of inequality</b> (RII) is a regression-based index which summarizes the magnitude of <a href=\"/wiki/Socio-economic_status\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Socio-economic status\">socio-economic status</a> (SES) as a source of <a href=\"/wiki/Health_disparities\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Health disparities\">inequalities</a> in health. RII is useful because it takes into account the size of the population and the relative disadvantage experienced by different groups.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The disease outcome is regressed on the proportion of the population that has a higher position in the hierarchy.\n</p><p>The RII is particularly valuable when comparing risk factors (independent variables) that are on very different scales (e.g. low SES, low <a href=\"/wiki/IQ\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"IQ\">IQ</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Cigarette_smoking\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cigarette smoking\">cigarette smoking</a>). The RII is calculated in the following way:<sup id=\"cite_ref-Batty2006_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Batty2006-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify\" title=\"Wikipedia:Please clarify\"><span title=\"The text near this tag may need clarification or removal of jargon. (March 2011)\">clarification needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<ol><li>Rank cases on each of the variables</li>\n<li>For tied ranks and for categorical variables, assign the mean rank</li>\n<li>Divide the ranks by the sample size, creating a value ranging from 0 to 1</li></ol>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Interpretation_of_RII\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Interpretation of RII</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Limitations_of_RII\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Limitations of RII</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Interpretation_of_RII\">Interpretation of RII</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Relative_index_of_inequality&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Interpretation of RII\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The interpretation of RII is similar to the <a href=\"/wiki/Relative_risk\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Relative risk\">relative risk</a>. It summarizes the relative risk for the most advantaged group (at the top of the hierarchy) compared to the least advantaged group (at the bottom of the hierarchy). This interpretation assumes that the variables have been scored so that higher scores are consistent with increased risk. For example, an RII of 1.88 (95% <a href=\"/wiki/Confidence_intervals\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Confidence intervals\">confidence intervals</a> 1.27 to 2.77), an indicator of low SES, on the risk of long term illness, implies that those in the most deprived group are 1.88 times more likely to experience illness than those in the least deprived group.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Batty2006_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Batty2006-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Limitations_of_RII\">Limitations of RII</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Relative_index_of_inequality&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Limitations of RII\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>One disadvantage of the RII is that it may capitalize on skewed data, inflating the apparent relative risk. A second limitation is that a large RII may arise for two reasons. First, it may represent a large effect of SES on disease. Second, it may reflect large differences between those with the most SES and those with the least (i.e. large inequalities in SES itself).\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Relative_index_of_inequality&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Mackenbach, Johan; Anton Kunst (1997). \"Measuring the magnitude of socio-economic inequalities in health: An overview of available measures illustrated with two examples from Europe\". <i>Social Science &amp; Medicine</i>. <b>44</b> (6): 757\u2013771. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1016/S0277-9536%2896%2900073-1\">10.1016/S0277-9536(96)00073-1</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Social+Science+%26+Medicine&amp;rft.atitle=Measuring+the+magnitude+of+socio-economic+inequalities+in+health%3A+An+overview+of+available+measures+illustrated+with+two+examples+from+Europe&amp;rft.volume=44&amp;rft.issue=6&amp;rft.pages=757-771&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2FS0277-9536%2896%2900073-1&amp;rft.aulast=Mackenbach&amp;rft.aufirst=Johan&amp;rft.au=Anton+Kunst&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARelative+index+of+inequality\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Batty2006-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Batty2006_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Batty2006_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Batty, David; Geoff Der; Sally Macintyre; Ian Deary (2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1397779\">\"Does IQ explain socioeconomic inequalities in health? Evidence from a population based cohort study in the west of Scotland\"</a>. <i>BMJ</i>. <b>332</b> (7541): 580\u2013584. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1136/bmj.38723.660637.AE\">10.1136/bmj.38723.660637.AE</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Central\" title=\"PubMed Central\">PMC</a>&#160;<span class=\"plainlinks\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1397779\">1397779</a>&#8239;<img alt=\"Freely accessible\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/9px-Lock-green.svg.png\" title=\"Freely accessible\" width=\"9\" height=\"14\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/14px-Lock-green.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/18px-Lock-green.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"813\" /></span>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16452104\">16452104</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=BMJ&amp;rft.atitle=Does+IQ+explain+socioeconomic+inequalities+in+health%3F+Evidence+from+a+population+based+cohort+study+in+the+west+of+Scotland&amp;rft.volume=332&amp;rft.issue=7541&amp;rft.pages=580-584&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC1397779&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F16452104&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1136%2Fbmj.38723.660637.AE&amp;rft.aulast=Batty&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rft.au=Geoff+Der&amp;rft.au=Sally+Macintyre&amp;rft.au=Ian+Deary&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC1397779&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARelative+index+of+inequality\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Relative_index_of_inequality&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Sergeant, J. C.; Firth, D (2005). \"Relative index of inequality: definition, estimation, and inference\". <i><a href=\"/wiki/Biostatistics_(journal)\" title=\"Biostatistics (journal)\">Biostatistics</a></i>. <b>7</b> (2): 213\u2013224. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1093/biostatistics/kxj002\">10.1093/biostatistics/kxj002</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16192414\">16192414</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Biostatistics&amp;rft.atitle=Relative+index+of+inequality%3A+definition%2C+estimation%2C+and+inference&amp;rft.volume=7&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=213-224&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1093%2Fbiostatistics%2Fkxj002&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F16192414&amp;rft.aulast=Sergeant&amp;rft.aufirst=J.+C.&amp;rft.au=Firth%2C+D&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARelative+index+of+inequality\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Moreno-Betancur, M; Latouche, A; Menvielle, G; Kunst, A. E.; Rey, G (2015). \"Relative index of inequality and slope index of inequality: a structured regression framework for estimation\". <i><a href=\"/wiki/Epidemiology_(journal)\" title=\"Epidemiology (journal)\">Epidemiology</a></i>. <b>26</b> (4): 518\u2013527. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1097/EDE.0000000000000311\">10.1097/EDE.0000000000000311</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26000548\">26000548</a>.</cite><span title=\"c